&Titan Help
#What is Titan?
Titan Computer Environment (TCE) is a comprehensive desktop environment designed specifically for blind and visually impaired users. The system features high accessibility, an intuitive interface, and full customization capabilities tailored to individual user needs.

#System Requirements
Operating System: Windows 10 or newer
Memory: 512 MB RAM
Storage: 700 MB (with Python interpreter for TCE applications) or 60 MB (without interpreter and TCE application support)

#Graphical Interface Keyboard Shortcuts
Ctrl+Tab - switch between application list and games list. Visually impaired users can also use the toolbar for mouse navigation
Tab - switch between application/games list and status bar
Shift+F10 - activate context menu for selected item (TCE application or game)
Alt - activate main program menu

#Application System
Titan applications are independent programs written in Python or compiled to executable files (.exe). The only element connecting TCE with an application is the appropriate configuration entry. All default TCE applications are developed according to TCE standards, characterized by simplicity, intuitiveness, and configurability.

An application can be installed as a plain directory, or as a single packaged .TCA file - see the "Packaging Add-ons (.TCA/.TCD)" section below.

#Games System
Titan offers full support for TCE games and external entertainment applications. The system does not include built-in games by default. Titan also automatically detects installed Steam and Battle.net games.

Information for developers: Documentation for creating applications and games is available in the titan/data/docu/programming guide directory

#Components
Components are background extensions that add new functionality to Titan - integrations, readers, accessibility tools, and more. Manage components in the Component Manager, where you can enable and disable them. Some components add their own settings category, or their own view in the main panel (switched with Ctrl+Tab).

#Gamepad Modes
Titan supports full gamepad navigation. Built-in modes are: System, Controller, Screen Reader, and Screen Keyboard.

Holding a bumper (LB or RB) for about a second switches the control mode - LB goes back to the previous mode, RB moves to the next one. Developers can add custom gamepad modes (e.g. document readers, media control) - these join the same mode-switching cycle.

#Speech Engines (TitanTTS)
Titan speaks through the selected speech engine - this can be a system engine (SAPI5, eSpeak, macOS Speech, Speech Dispatcher) or one of the TitanTTS plugin engines (e.g. Milena, ElevenLabs, DECtalk, Eloquence, and others, depending on installed engines). Change the engine, voice, rate, and pitch in Settings, under the sound/speech section.

#Packaging Add-ons (.TCA/.TCD)
Applications, games, and other add-ons (components, launchers, Titan IM modules, gamepad modes, TTS engines, widgets, statusbar applets) can be distributed as a single file instead of a directory:
- applications and games: `.TCA` extension
- every other add-on kind: `.TCD` extension

This is a custom compressed format - deliberately not a regular zip archive, so it cannot be opened in 7-Zip or Windows Explorer as an archive.

To install such a file, simply double-click the .TCA/.TCD file in Windows Explorer (Titan registers this file association automatically at startup) - Titan copies it into the right data directory and either launches it immediately (applications/games) or makes it available (other add-on kinds). These files can also be uploaded to and downloaded from the Titan-Net app repository.

Developers can find the full packaging instructions in the guides under data/docu/programming_guide/.

#Titan IM
The Titan IM module provides integration with popular messengers: Telegram, Messenger, and WhatsApp, as well as Titan's own social network (Titan-Net) and Elten (see the separate sections below). Due to technical limitations, WhatsApp and Messenger operate as web applications integrated with TCE through dedicated scripts.

#Status Bar
The status bar displays key system information such as: current time, battery level, system volume, and network connection status.

#Invisible Interface
After minimizing the main window, Titan automatically switches to invisible interface mode. This mode enables full program control from any system application without the need to switch windows.

#Invisible Interface Keyboard Shortcuts
The Ctrl+Shift combination serves as the primary modifier in the invisible interface. In documentation, shortcuts are presented as "Titan+key" for simplified notation.

Titan+arrows - navigation in four directions (up, down, left, right). In default mode (outside widgets), up/down arrows switch between categories, and left/right switch between elements in a given category. In widgets, arrows provide standard directional navigation
Titan+Enter - activate selected element
Titan+Backspace or Titan+Esc - exit current widget
Tilde key (~) - toggle Titan UI mode (if option is active)

#Titan UI Mode
Titan UI mode enables interface navigation using only arrow keys, without the need to hold additional modifiers. This provides even greater user comfort for those preferring simplified navigation.

#Titan IM and Elten
Elten integration in Titan IM is in beta, which means some features may not work correctly.
If you are a moderator of important groups or of the Elten portal itself, we recommend using the official client. You cannot create an Elten account from within TCE, and this is intentional - this integration is meant for users who already have an account on that portal.

#Titan-Net
Since two versions ago, Titan has had its own portal, called Titan-Net. It lets TCE users get in touch with and connect to the community.

#The Cerberus System
Cerberus provides active protection for Titan-Net users and the server. It's a system that detects and blocks potential attacks such as brute force attempts or account break-ins. If Cerberus detects that an attacker may be able to breach the server, there are 3 possible responses:
Alert - recognition of an attacking or intruding user
Lockdown - nobody can log in to the Titan-Net server
Cerberus mode - Titan-Net is in active-protection mode, no incoming connection is let through. Moderators have access to the system logs.

#Update Model
Titan does not update frequently, but each new version fixes bugs reported by users, and new features are often added along the way. Updates are released roughly every 1-2 months.